Youtube is a beast unto itself.
Thus there is a special program, yt-dlp,
designed to download video or audio from youtube.com.
I'm not sure what yt-dlp means,
but I remember it as download a dollop (dlp) of youtube.

As I write this, yt-dlp does not work as distributed (debian), but the latest does work.
there is a reason for this.
Youtube is antagonistic to our needs.
Facebook shuts us out by being excessively graphical,
and using every javascript feature known to man,
but they would say, if asked,
"We didn't mean to shut you out.
You can always use a commercial browser with voice over technology.
We really want you to use our services."
That's what they would say.
In contrast, youtube does not want us,
or anyone, to download videos from their servers to their computers.
It opens the door to copyright infringement.
Everybody can steal songs off of youtube without paying the artist.
It's a legitimate concern.
Therefore, youtube constantly does things to their website,
so only the commercial browsers can view the videos. Hence you can "watch"
a copyrighted video, on a one-time basis, including commercials.
Unfortunately, we, (people who use alternate browsers),
have to copy it to listen to it.
We have to do the very thing youtube doesn't want us to do.
youtube creates restrictions hand-in-hand with the commercial browsers,
and in response, yt-dlp is constantly trying to get around these restrictions.
Back and forth, year after year, it's a game of cat and mouse.
For now the cat has the upper hand. ðŸ˜¼
